Date: 1 Sep 2000 19:34:08 -0400
From: Eleanor Kellon <kell@epix.net>
Source: Reuters, 1 Sep 2000 7:02 PM ET [edited

Seventh New York and first New Jersey Resident Confirmed to Have West Nile
Virus
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
TRENTON: A 43-year-old man has become the first person in New Jersey to
contract the mosquito-born West Nile virus that killed seven people in the
New York area last summer, State Health Officials said on Friday. The man,
who's name was withheld, is recovering at his home in Jersey City. New
Jersey State Health Department spokesman Dennis McGowan said the man fell
ill 6 Aug 2000 and was hospitalized on 10 Aug 2000. The patient went home
the next day, and blood samples taken to test for the virus were sent to
the Federal Centers for Disease Control. Officials confirmed the result on
Friday.
On Friday, 1 Sep 2000, New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said that a
61-year-old Staten Island man had become the seventh person in the city
this year to test positive for the virus. The man became ill on 4 Aug 2000
with muscle weakness and encephalitis, was admitted to a local hospital on
6 Aug 2000 and released on 11 Aug 2000. The New York State Department of
Health received test results on Thursday confirming the man ad contracted
West Nile virus.
This year in the United States no-one has died from the disease, which has
been found in infected birds from Massachusetts to New Jersey. Since July,
New York City has been conducting an aggressive insecticide spraying
campaign throughout the city.
--
Eleanor Kellon
<kell@epix.net>
